WEBVTT

00:00.800 --> 00:02.768
Don't try what you're
about to see at home.

00:02.770 --> 00:04.336
We're what you call experts.

00:04.338 --> 00:05.804
Okay, go.

00:05.806 --> 00:07.072
Ooh!

00:08.074 --> 00:10.109
On this episode of "Mythbusters"...

00:10.111 --> 00:13.746
Gravity-defying legend
Nik Wallenda

00:13.748 --> 00:18.617
Prepares to master
mother nature's grandest canyon.

00:19.619 --> 00:20.953
This is tough.

00:20.955 --> 00:23.255
It's not just mental,
it's physical.

00:23.257 --> 00:25.524
A walk into history

00:25.526 --> 00:28.761
That Adam and Jamie are
on their way to witness...

00:28.763 --> 00:31.930
<i>Destination --</i>
<i>the roll in the rock.</i>

00:31.932 --> 00:34.433
<i>Turn right 200 yards.</i>

00:34.435 --> 00:35.701
...They hope.

00:35.703 --> 00:37.770
Where is everybody?

00:37.772 --> 00:39.405
I was just kind of expecting
more people.

00:39.407 --> 00:42.841
I mean, crossing the canyon
on a wire is, like, a big event.

00:43.309 --> 00:46.378
<i>Recalculating</i>
<i>destination.</i>

00:47.214 --> 00:49.148
This can't be right.

00:49.150 --> 00:51.283
<i>Destination --</i>
<i>roll in the rock.</i>

00:51.285 --> 00:53.185
<i>50 yards.</i>

00:53.187 --> 00:56.121
I'm not even sure
this is a road.

00:56.123 --> 01:00.926
<i>You have reached your</i>
<i>destination.</i>

01:00.928 --> 01:03.028
Thanks a lot, lady.

01:06.033 --> 01:07.332
There's your problem.

01:07.334 --> 01:09.835
Shall we call for backup?

01:09.837 --> 01:10.369
No signal.

01:10.371 --> 01:14.106
Great.
Let's go see where we are.

01:20.181 --> 01:20.846
Yeah, we're lost.

01:20.848 --> 01:24.283
Not only are we lost.
Our car is totally junked.

01:24.285 --> 01:27.219
We're out of gas and our
navigation's up the spout.

01:27.221 --> 01:29.054
Well,
what do you think's next?

01:29.957 --> 01:31.757
Got to figure out a way
to get out of here.

01:31.759 --> 01:34.560
Wouldn't it be nice if we had
a trunk full of duct tape?

01:37.398 --> 01:39.364
Oh, my arms
have about given out.

01:39.366 --> 01:41.600
Yep. Hold on to your hats.

01:43.636 --> 01:45.270
Come on.
Give me some of that.

01:45.272 --> 01:47.940
Can Adam
and Jamie's favorite fabric...

01:47.942 --> 01:51.210
Looks bad. Feels good.

01:51.212 --> 01:53.245
...Defeat desolate deserts...

01:53.247 --> 01:55.047
You're Nik Wallenda,
aren't you?

01:55.049 --> 01:56.348
I am one and the same.

01:56.350 --> 01:58.817
...Conquer colossal climbs...

01:58.819 --> 02:00.786
People do this
for recreation?!

02:00.788 --> 02:03.255
...And navigate
raging river rapids?

02:03.257 --> 02:04.756
aah!

02:04.758 --> 02:08.560
This is
the duct tape canyon special.

02:09.596 --> 02:11.763
Yeah!
whoo!

02:13.399 --> 02:16.268
Who are the Mythbusters?

02:16.970 --> 02:18.070
Adam Savage...

02:18.072 --> 02:20.072
This is science in action.

02:20.074 --> 02:22.107
...And Jamie Hyneman.

02:22.109 --> 02:22.608
Bye-bye.

02:22.610 --> 02:27.412
Between them, more than 30 years
of special-effects experience.

02:27.414 --> 02:30.449
Together with Grant Imahara...

02:30.451 --> 02:32.584
That is crazy!

02:32.586 --> 02:33.519
...Kari Byron...

02:34.455 --> 02:35.621
...And Tory Belleci.

02:35.623 --> 02:37.556
Come along
for the journey.

02:37.558 --> 02:40.692
They don't just tell
the myths.

02:40.694 --> 02:42.661
They put them to the test.

02:42.663 --> 02:45.797
-- <font color="#ffff00">Captions by Vitac</font> --
<font color="#00ffff">www.vitac.com</font>

02:45.799 --> 02:49.334
Captions paid for by
Discovery Communications

02:49.336 --> 02:52.504
Pack your packaging,
put on your prom wear --

02:52.506 --> 02:57.676
It's "Mythbusters"
versus wild west.

02:57.678 --> 02:59.645
As we've made obvious
in the past,

02:59.647 --> 03:02.314
We have a passion
for the duct tape.

03:02.316 --> 03:03.282
It's handy stuff.

03:03.284 --> 03:04.850
Fun for the whole family.

03:05.386 --> 03:07.252
We've used it
to make a sailboat.

03:07.254 --> 03:07.853
Yee-haw!

03:07.855 --> 03:09.388
We've used it
to make a bridge...

03:09.390 --> 03:11.390
A cannon...

03:11.392 --> 03:12.457
...A crash barrier...
Ah!

03:12.459 --> 03:14.726
...We've used it to escape
from a deserted island.

03:16.564 --> 03:19.698
And since we've proven it's
the ultimate survival tool,

03:19.700 --> 03:21.300
We never leave home
without it.

03:21.302 --> 03:22.167
Which is lucky,
because

03:22.169 --> 03:24.303
Before we got interrupted
by the opening credits,

03:24.305 --> 03:26.438
We were dressed for success
and heading on our way

03:26.440 --> 03:29.408
To watch Nik Wallenda
walk across the grand canyon.

03:29.410 --> 03:31.343
But our gps had other plans,

03:31.345 --> 03:34.880
Steered us to the canyon's edge
in the middle of nowhere

03:34.882 --> 03:37.616
With nothing but a trunk
full of duct tape.

03:37.618 --> 03:38.450
We need a plan.

03:38.452 --> 03:39.084
Well, that's easy.

03:39.086 --> 03:40.886
All we have to do
is go down to the river

03:40.888 --> 03:43.088
And follow it
back to civilization.

03:43.090 --> 03:44.289
Exactly.

03:44.291 --> 03:45.991
That's -- what? What?

03:47.861 --> 03:50.862
Okay, apparently it's
not gonna happen that way.

03:50.864 --> 03:52.664
Meddling producers.

03:52.666 --> 03:54.600
seriously?

03:54.602 --> 03:56.001
okay.

03:56.003 --> 03:58.971
All right, so apparently
we're not at the canyon's edge.

03:58.973 --> 04:01.173
We are stranded literally
in the middle of nowhere.

04:01.175 --> 04:02.307
We have to go find
the canyon

04:02.309 --> 04:03.909
And the temperature is hovering,
where?

04:03.911 --> 04:06.445
yeah, right around zero.

04:06.447 --> 04:06.778
Hmm.

04:06.780 --> 04:08.180
Well, fortunately,
I brought along

04:08.182 --> 04:09.915
A bunch
of extra bubble pack.

04:09.917 --> 04:11.550
Excellent.
I love that stuff, too.

04:11.552 --> 04:12.751
Well,
I guess all that's left

04:12.753 --> 04:14.720
Is for us to get zapped
back out there.

04:14.722 --> 04:17.289
So, editors,
will you do our honors?

04:19.158 --> 04:20.158
That was weird.

04:20.160 --> 04:20.791
Artistic license.

04:20.793 --> 04:24.596
All right, so our car's out
of gas, our gps doesn't work,

04:24.598 --> 04:29.001
We're dressed to the nines,
and we are completely lost.

04:29.003 --> 04:30.035
What do we do?

04:30.037 --> 04:31.837
Maybe we should take
inventory --

04:31.839 --> 04:33.272
See what we've got
to work with.

04:33.274 --> 04:34.139
Good enough. Let's do it.

04:34.141 --> 04:37.843
Yep, the first task
for our tuxedoed twosome

04:37.845 --> 04:39.544
Is to take stock.

04:39.546 --> 04:41.446
Jackpot.

04:41.448 --> 04:45.450
Because when stranded in
a remote and hostile location,

04:45.452 --> 04:48.220
It's the first
and most fundamental step

04:48.222 --> 04:53.091
Of any survival strategy --
assess your equipment.

04:53.093 --> 04:55.427
I found jelly beans.

04:55.429 --> 04:57.062
Oh, great.

04:57.064 --> 04:58.363
And beef jerky.

04:58.365 --> 05:00.132
Food and water is a start,

05:00.134 --> 05:03.969
But the real prize is
Jamie's stash of sticky stuff...

05:03.971 --> 05:05.437
What the...?

05:05.439 --> 05:06.905
...And packing that pops.

05:06.907 --> 05:08.674
I don't go anywhere
without duct tape.

05:08.676 --> 05:10.609
Wait till you see what I got
in the other bag.

05:10.611 --> 05:14.179
Over the years, I've
become really fond of duct tape,

05:14.181 --> 05:15.147
But there's one other material

05:15.149 --> 05:18.750
That I've added to my list --
bubble packing.

05:18.752 --> 05:21.353
You never know
when it'll come in handy.

05:21.355 --> 05:22.654
How about now?

05:22.656 --> 05:26.024
Because some hot couture
is required.

05:26.026 --> 05:27.492
Now, we're in the high desert,

05:27.494 --> 05:29.828
And you'd expect it
to be pretty hot.

05:29.830 --> 05:30.529
It is not hot at all.

05:30.531 --> 05:32.431
In fact, the temperature
out here is hovering

05:32.433 --> 05:34.633
Right around
0 degrees celsius --

05:34.635 --> 05:35.934
32 degrees fahrenheit.

05:35.936 --> 05:37.336
And while the tuxedo
does a fine job

05:37.338 --> 05:39.805
Of making me look darn good...

05:39.807 --> 05:42.174
...I am freezing my tuckus off.

05:42.176 --> 05:45.610
Luckily, we brought
a terrific insulator with us

05:45.612 --> 05:47.846
In the form
of this bubble packaging.

05:47.848 --> 05:49.514
You need some duct tape?

05:49.516 --> 05:49.981
Sure.

05:49.983 --> 05:52.918
The dynamic duo to the rescue.

05:52.920 --> 05:54.252
Tuckus-freezing temperatures

05:54.254 --> 05:57.089
Means plastic ponchos
all around.

05:57.091 --> 05:59.091
One of my favorite things.

05:59.093 --> 06:01.626
Looks bad. Feels good.

06:01.628 --> 06:05.731
I guess I shouldn't be surprised
at how effective this is,

06:05.733 --> 06:06.531
But I am.

06:06.533 --> 06:08.100
Gloves!

06:08.102 --> 06:09.568
These little air bubbles

06:09.570 --> 06:12.404
Are just like the bubbles
in foam rubber,

06:12.406 --> 06:13.772
And so, it's very insulating.

06:13.774 --> 06:16.775
With our
now less-than-debonair duo

06:16.777 --> 06:20.045
Cloaked against the cold,
it's time to take action.

06:20.047 --> 06:26.785
Cue the slow-mo for a dramatic,
cinematic scouting mission.

06:26.787 --> 06:29.855
Now, we know we're
in canyonland,

06:29.857 --> 06:30.989
And where there's a canyon,

06:30.991 --> 06:32.457
There's usually a river
at the bottom of it.

06:32.459 --> 06:37.629
And that'll be our most direct
route back to civilization.

06:37.631 --> 06:40.098
Hey,
that's what we want.

06:40.100 --> 06:44.436
But the thing is, we don't know
exactly where it is.

06:44.438 --> 06:47.205
So I figure we need
to find some high ground

06:47.207 --> 06:51.376
And see if we can get
a better view of the terrain.

06:51.378 --> 06:52.911
Oh, yeah.

06:52.913 --> 06:54.946
Not just better.

06:54.948 --> 06:57.716
The view is breathtaking...

06:57.718 --> 06:58.950
Literally.

06:58.952 --> 07:00.485
It's beautiful up here.

07:00.487 --> 07:03.255
hold on a second while I...

07:03.257 --> 07:03.889
Catch your breath.

07:03.891 --> 07:06.324
Have a heart attack
is what I was thinking.

07:06.326 --> 07:10.095
Heart-attack inducing,
but it was worth the effort.

07:10.097 --> 07:12.330
Salvation is in sight.

07:12.332 --> 07:14.299
There's our canyon.

07:14.301 --> 07:15.000
That's it all right.

07:15.002 --> 07:16.234
Oh, I'm glad
this was worth it.

07:16.236 --> 07:19.271
Well, it looks like
it's a long ways off,

07:19.273 --> 07:21.139
But now we know
here we're headed,

07:21.141 --> 07:23.375
So it's time to head
back to base camp

07:23.377 --> 07:24.576
And make
some preparations.

07:24.578 --> 07:27.813
And back at the broken-down car,

07:27.815 --> 07:29.414
There's two types of news.

07:29.416 --> 07:32.184
The good news is
we know where we're going.

07:32.186 --> 07:32.918
The bad news is there's

07:32.920 --> 07:34.619
Only a couple of hours
of daylight left,

07:34.621 --> 07:37.155
Which means we can't set out
until the morning.

07:37.157 --> 07:40.192
Shelter and warmth are crucial.

07:40.194 --> 07:44.696
So Jamie begins by building
a duct-tape bivouac.

07:44.698 --> 07:46.031
Well, that's one.

07:46.033 --> 07:49.100
With a bunch more,
I'll have myself a tent.

07:49.102 --> 07:51.703
And bright spark Adam,

07:51.705 --> 07:56.007
Planning on camping in the car,
has an idea.

07:56.009 --> 07:56.608
Freedom.

07:56.610 --> 07:58.743
Our sat-and-nav electrics
may be up the spout,

07:58.745 --> 07:59.778
But I'm willing to bet
this battery

07:59.780 --> 08:02.614
Still has enough charge
to create a spark.

08:02.616 --> 08:05.717
As long as I can create a spark,
I can make a fire.

08:05.719 --> 08:06.985
That's the theory.

08:06.987 --> 08:09.721
Okay, okay. Calm down.
Everybody calm down.

08:09.723 --> 08:12.624
But the wires
are too hot to handle.

08:12.626 --> 08:14.192
Look at how hot
I'm getting this.

08:14.194 --> 08:15.894
It's melting the cover
right off.

08:15.896 --> 08:17.762
It's getting hard to hold,
actually.

08:17.764 --> 08:18.430
Duct tape to the rescue.

08:18.432 --> 08:21.800
A little bit of insulation
from his favorite fabric

08:21.802 --> 08:25.170
Provides handy handles,
meaning...

08:25.172 --> 08:27.973
There it is! Come on.

08:27.975 --> 08:31.443
You can totally do this.

08:33.514 --> 08:35.914
This is happening for real.

08:35.916 --> 08:36.448
Oh, my gosh.

08:36.450 --> 08:39.751
Meanwhile, with the cold night
rapidly closing in,

08:39.753 --> 08:42.821
Jamie's shelter favors function
over form.

08:42.823 --> 08:45.690
This wasn't exactly what
I had in mind as far as a tent,

08:45.692 --> 08:48.326
But it'll keep the dew
off of me,

08:48.328 --> 08:49.361
It'll keep the wind off,

08:49.363 --> 08:53.331
And with a sleeping bag
made out of bubble packing,

08:53.333 --> 08:54.599
I'll be good to go.

08:54.601 --> 08:57.736
Yep, they started out stranded,

08:57.738 --> 09:01.172
Lost in the unforgiving expanse
of the canyonlands,

09:01.174 --> 09:04.242
But with a little
mythbusting ingenuity,

09:04.244 --> 09:06.211
Come sunset...

09:06.213 --> 09:07.679
Not a bad day.

09:07.681 --> 09:11.650
...They have
a romantic, fire-lit dinner...

09:11.652 --> 09:12.217
Jelly bean?

09:12.219 --> 09:13.952
...Know where they're headed...

09:13.954 --> 09:15.887
Tomorrow,
to the canyons.

09:15.889 --> 09:18.256
...And a cozy campsite for two.

09:18.258 --> 09:19.558
We're gonna be toasty.

09:19.560 --> 09:21.092
Duct tape and bubble pack --

09:21.094 --> 09:24.329
The choice
for all discerning survivors.

09:24.331 --> 09:25.864
This is just like a duvet.

09:25.866 --> 09:27.465
Good night, Jamie.

09:27.467 --> 09:29.501
Good night.

09:29.503 --> 09:31.202
Good night.

09:37.476 --> 09:42.247
But when day two does dawn,
our desperate duo...

09:42.249 --> 09:43.014
Water's all gone.

09:43.016 --> 09:44.883
...Will discover
just what it takes

09:44.885 --> 09:49.688
To conquer the hard,
cold canyonlands.

